The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe you are .
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all the services as their Western European partners.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classic ones go cheap.
He may not be gone for long.
We have written many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the CTA, which pointed out that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the European Commission's latest steps to regulate roaming charges, a paradox may emerge - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really wants to fight.
It may seem paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks and a penetration rate of over 100 percent.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to play on the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák has often said that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a traditional operator with its own network probably has little chance (after all, it would probably be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market brought significant price reductions, which the traditional operators had to accept.
And before the likes of Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile came on the market, the voices in the UK were very similar to the voices in the UK.
But it turns out that there is a place for these operators, and they can be really successful.
And we don't have to go too far to find examples.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator managed to attract more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not entail the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining a mobile network.
In a world like this, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low-cost - offering cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at at least half the price of its competitors.
But as the Mobilking case in Poland shows, it can be a good bet to target an untrained audience.
This operator is targeting men specifically.
"The right guys are choosing Mobilking - a carrier they like and trust", says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual carrier.
It's hard to say if a similar concept as in Poland could be applied here.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: 'The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated in terms of the range of services offered.'
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say the mobile operators
It seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about expanding this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic are not looking very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region", Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic were not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they are doing everything they can to prevent any potential competitor from emerging.
GTS Novera has been open about its interest in launching a virtual mobile operator for some time, as it wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
'We are keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
The sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them", says Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesman.
Maybe it's just a flash for a better time.
From unofficial information, we should expect to see the first virtual operator before the end of the year.
For now, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
'At the moment we do not think there is room for a full-fledged virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a complex and serious project in this area,' Vlastimil Sršň from Telefónica O2's press department told Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2: "So far we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build".
He adds: "It's unlikely that any virtual operator will appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
We would have to have a concrete agreement on the table at this point to be able to think in this short timeframe".
Vodafone is focusing on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
That's what we consider the most profitable from a customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for high-speed mobile internet.'
Responsible authorities - with operators on hand
The Commission considers that the measure is compatible with the common market in so far as it is compatible with the internal market.
So why facilitate the entry of such a competitor?
The fact that operators can pull together when they need to is also evidenced by the debate surrounding the creation of the U:phone.
Perhaps the biggest push towards the CTU came with the emergence of U-phone from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information on the OCT website.
But now, U:fon is the perfect argument for not allowing a virtual operator.
Martina Kemr added: 'The competitive environment in the mobile market has been recently strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on it and, in particular, on its services.'
Given this approach of mobile operators, it is striking that the Czech regulators are completely uninterested.
It is not just the position of the CTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to interfere with competition.
These are the exclusive responsibility of the Competition Authority (the OOHS).
But he took his typical attitude to the whole issue.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional operators,' said Kristián Chalupa from the External Relations Department of the OHCHR in response to our inquiry.
The representatives of the operators are not surprised by such statements.
It is more than a duty for an authority which is supposed to represent consumers' interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses his position on the market.
In particular, Kristián Chalupa adds: 'In foreign countries, where virtual operators are common, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the reduction of prices for mobile telephone services.'
But apparently the pressure to have the market function properly and the price drop is not in the interests of the OOHS.
What is truly shocking about this case is the touching convergence of the three mobile operators, as reflected in their reactions.
The question of whether it's really just a coincidence is entirely self-evident.
Just as the exact same price of gasoline at gas stations is surely a matter of chance and fierce competition.
"The Authority has not found any evidence of anti-competitive conduct in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have correspondingly increased responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are also likely to be lacking for the telecoms regulator", Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of a dominant position is one of many points of dispute.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets by the OCTs, according to which telecommunications is a single market from a competition point of view.
Of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts suggest that the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator -- quite logically -- has a monopoly on its network.
So it's bound to be dominant in a certain segment.
Even if we reject this argument, it should at least be alarming for OOHS that the three mobile operators are behaving in a strikingly similar way.
However, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
The imposition of liability on the CTU is a fairly common trick in telecommunications, which the ODNI takes its hands off the matter.
We've met him on a number of similar occasions.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the CTU's powers to the area of competition in telecommunications had not succeeded in being enforced, although many experts had promised that this would improve the situation.
The OHS representatives must know this more than well, but their interests are clearly elsewhere.
It's the way it goes when no one's looking
However, the operation of pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but which are only partially public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
The own mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The prices of these companies are usually only available to a select few.
The magic is that the company acts as a typical business customer to the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer, it receives special pricing (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial terms of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If the cases you are talking about were to occur, they could be breaches of contract terms that we would be dealing with and could result in termination of cooperation with the company", Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
But it's very unlikely that this kind of activity would not have been passed on to the responsible people from the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, thousands of customers could be affected.
None of the operators is preventing such a procedure.
The fact that these companies make substantial profits does not mean that they are threatened by their own official marketing, unlike the real virtual operators.
Miroslav Čepický points out the potential problems: "The law allows for such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
Moreover, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name and cannot be used fully as a normal mobile operator customer.'
But that's what should be the least bit weird.
In addition, it opens up another question for the OHS.
If mobile operators are turning a blind eye to a similar practice, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the OHIM has a relatively strong authority to detect such activity and, if it does not wish to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators that they have no knowledge of such activity and that their business conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive
As has been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a marked decrease in the price of services.
In practice, however, in all countries where virtual operators have emerged, the traditional operators have tried to prevent their emergence to a greater or lesser extent.
The arguments used by them were virtually identical - too small, too saturated market, quality of service problems, etc.
But in developed countries, it was at these moments that regulatory agencies stepped in, not to protect the interests of the mobile operators, but to protect the interests of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they have succeeded in creating the first virtual operator and have been joined by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are throwing this whole thing around like a hot potato.
In our experience, we can't help but feel that a lack of clarity in the powers of the Commission is more than adequate in these cases.
But let's not throw the gun at the man.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and a virtual operator appears in our country soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators has allowed the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the OHIM will hardly be able to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other applicants.
And maybe we'll stop calling it "the other day" than the rest of Europe.
