Choose the Best
Listen to four renditions of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek, on the occasion of the Czech Republic's National Day, officially released a new recording of the national anthem, Where Is My Home?
The anthem was newly recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions - with male or female solo singing, in choral presentation and instrumental version.
The song was sung by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the adaptation of the anthem are Otakar Jeremáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had previously told Czech Radio that he had deliberately chosen singers with young representative voices who were distinct and popular to sing solo variants.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both of them and the congregation had clear diction, that the text was well understood, that they were in agreement", he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Kde domov můj" was first heard in 1834 on the stages of the Stavovsky Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetan Tyla, supplemented by the music of František Škroupa.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously embraced it.
The first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem after the formation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the formation of the independent Czech Republic.
