Sudetenland wanted a referendum after the US
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans asked for the incorporation of Šumava into the United States.
It's from a letter that's in the South Bohemian Science Library.
If we can't be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
It was with this desire that some groups of Sudeten Germans reportedly turned to the president of the United States in 1945.
This is apparent, among other things, from a letter that was preserved in a private archive and is now in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans from Český Krumlov are asking in a letter to the American president not to allow the return of the "Shumava County" - seized by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we want to be really sure in words that American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", the letter, signed "People who have the fate of the Shumawi at heart", reads.
Because the annexation of Czechoslovakia gives the Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national nature - only hope for brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the protectorate of Šumava for the present and eternal times.
"We cannot believe that you would, regardless of the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants, grant this territory to some foreign state which oppresses and excludes minorities and by no means contributes to the victory of the Allies", the letter says.
The reason why authors cannot sign is allegedly fear of the vengeful "Czech oppressors".
If the US president had doubts about the mindset of the Shumawi Germans, it would have been enough for him to hold a referendum in Shumawi County on whether its residents wanted to become part of the US or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the letter's text may sound a bit naive in today's postwar history, some historians say it aptly reflects the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Although the Czech Germans had at least a hint that they would be expelled from the republic, few of them even considered such a possibility.
