Even rats have feelings
When rats or cockroaches run away from danger, do they also feel fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals have feelings too.
But how can we tell if they feel the same way when they behave in a way that is similar to our own?
For years, the online magazine Edge has featured contributions from well-known scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of selected answers to the question "What do you believe to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove it yet, when we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, at least, we can hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But as soon as we start to engage with a different species and open up questions of perception or consciousness in general, we enter a terrain of incompatibility because the hardware doesn't match.
When in danger, the rat does what many other animals do: It will pretend to be dead, run away, or attack.
Humans behave similarly, which some scientists have inferred to be a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to animal experience.
This is because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always involve the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its contribution to short-term memory and executive or managerial functions).
This vast area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, between knowing who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there's reason to believe that humans are different even from other primates.
Another dramatic quirk could be hidden by the linguistic nature of man: because so much of his perception is tied to language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could rule out animals.
But even if consciousness did not matter in language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably be different from most of our states of consciousness.
So it's hard to figure out what consciousness might look like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured or, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then we face great problems in examining it.
Most of my discoveries relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study the processes in the animal mind regardless of their content, and that's exactly what's happening in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially in the visualization example.
But this approach, which was pioneered by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: they may be identical, but they may not be either.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the nefrontal cortex for visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I deduce that an emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we refer to as "fear" is the mental state we find ourselves in when the activity of a defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) takes advantage of the operational memory.
And seen from this angle, sensation is closely associated with those areas of the cortex that are characteristic of primates, and especially humans.
And in connection with linguistic nature, there is a subtle gradation of perception, because we can use words and grammar to distinguish and categorize states, to assign them to others as well as to ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the cortex and brainstem areas dedicated to bodily sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brainstem.
And because this network hasn't changed much in the course of human evolution, it could easily be involved in the feelings experienced by many species.
I can't dispute that, theoretically, but I can't prove it.
Pankseep argues that what we see as fear in rats and humans is probably felt in both organisms in the same way: But how can we verify, Pankseep says, that rats and humans feel the same thing when they behave similarly?
The cockroach flees danger - does it feel fear?
In my view, mere similarity in behavior cannot prove a similarity in experience.
It's true that the neural comparison takes us further: rats and humans have similar brainstems, whereas cockroaches have no brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for the feelings?
And even if we could prove it in a human, how would we prove it in a rat?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I'm looking more at emotional behavior than emotional perception in rats.
Anyway, in this case, we can expect to see progress at the neural level if we measure the same thing in rats and humans.
I'm not studying language and consciousness in the rat, nor am I studying feelings, because I don't know if they exist.
This may be considered shortsighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than repeatedly throw myself against the wall.
I'm a practical emotionalist.
