Effectively reaching Hispanic voters is a tricky business.
Barack Obama's education agenda is just proving it.
The Obama campaign notes that "African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students", which is true.
To combat such performance gaps, Obama's education agenda specifically promotes, among other things, "transitional bilingual education" for those who are just learning English.
The question for Barack Obama, however, remains whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in narrowing the performance gap.
Take Sixth Street Prep, a charter elementary school in the East Los Angeles district.
The students at this school are overwhelmingly Hispanic from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently been admitted, are new to English.
Yet, in the 2008 state math tests, the incredible 100 percent of fourth graders made it to the top.
Almost as impressive, ninety-three percent of fourth-graders scored in the top tier of the state's English language and literature tests.
This incredible success was achieved by a different method than the one Obama prefers.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of ability and an unforgiving approach.
Also, and this is something Obama should take note of, according to Linda Mikels, the Sixth Street principal, the school's approach to teaching English to those who are just learning is "full immersion".
Immersion in English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in teaching.
Miss Mikels, who is against bilingual education, told me, "We had a tremendous success with a brand-new student from Mexico - after 12 months, you would walk into a classroom and not know who it was".
"It works", she declared, "it works for us".
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for what other schools with large percentages of Hispanic and English learners should look like?
The school's performance should make the answer self-evident, but his own party's educational agenda (the National Education Association is a long-time advocate of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education obscure Obama's prediction of the answer.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue when he said people should stop worrying about "English-only" laws.
Instead, he said, "You should make sure your children speak Spanish".
If Obama really wants to erase the performance gap, he should think carefully about the education models that work, rather than ridicule and trivialize them.
