Then on Sunday, he watched the second quarter develop, as the Jets turned a scoreless game into a sleepy drive.
"I have never seen anything like it", said Ellis.
The second quarter began after the Jets and Arizona Cardinals had matched their exhausted play against the grim clouds above.
Then quarterback Brett Favre sent Laveranuese Coles to a 12-yard touchdown run, perfectly signaling an afternoon in which their budding partnership had moved on by miles.
Favre sent Coles off for two more touchdowns in the fourth quarter, including one where the cornerback went down, and another 10 seconds before halftime.
"It was nothing special", Favre said of all his passing to Coles.
"He's a hell of a player.
We communicated well, no matter what people thought".
While Favre and Coles were fighting, the defense attacked Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner.
Cornerback Darelle Revis caught a pass from a stray and returned it 32 yards for a touchdown.
Safety Eric Smith has the next pass and he catches it.
Linebacker David Bowens forced Warner to fumble the ball.
The last throw of the ball, the fumble that Bowens forced, was perhaps the best ever.
The Cardinals got the ball 10 seconds to play, and after the Jets got the ball back, Jay Feely kicked a 20-yard field goal to give them a 34-0 lead.
That's the most the Jets have ever scored in a quarter.
Jets coach Eric Mangini, when asked to describe the madness, said, "Second quarter or third quarter?"
When told that both - the Jets allowed 21 unanswered points in the third quarter - Mangini said: "I can tell you that I enjoyed the second quarter much more than the third.
"Many points have been dropped in a short period of time".
The late Gebreselassie has broken his own world record
Haile Gebreselassie of Ethiopia once again showed why many consider him the greatest distance runner of all time, when he broke his own world record in the Berlin Marathon on Sunday, becoming the first person to run a 26.2-mile race in under two hours and four minutes.
His victory on a pleasantly flat track in 2:03:59 beat his previous time of 2:04:26 set last year in Berlin by 27 seconds.
Gebreselassie, 35, has set the 26th world record of his career, which is really incredibly broad - he has broken the world record or at least is the world champion at all distances from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebreselassie missed the Beijing Olympic marathon because he feared - perhaps too much in retrospect - that the air pollution would exacerbate his asthma problems.
Instead, he promised to run in Berlin.
In almost perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish - Gebreselassie won Sunday with a lightning-fast average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
As track runners like Gebreselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya have focused on the longer track, the marathon record has dropped by more than two minutes in the past decade since Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin in 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday's victory, Gebreselassie told reporters that he had a leg cramp two weeks ago and missed a week of training.
The break obviously energized him more than it sustained him.
"I'm so happy", Gebreselassie said to the reporters.
"Everything was perfect.
I started again a week ago and I was a little doubtful today, but everything was fine".
He was also criticized - especially in Kenya, East Africa's rival to Ethiopia - for allegedly over-planning his races, generally avoiding the world's top marathoners, relying on race drivers as if it were a race on a track, and setting world records over his sense of competition.
But this criticism can hardly diminish Gebreselassie's enormous running ability.
Maintained at the pace of the four Kenyans, Gebreselassie reached the half in a time of 1:02:04.
After the drivers had passed out, Gebreselassie was chased by two Kenyan elite runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi.
With just under three miles to go, Gebreselassie finally caught and ran to Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in a time of 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenková, a native of Kazakhstan and now a citizen of Germany, finished the excellent year with the seventh fastest time in history of 2:19:19.
The record time of 2:15:25 is held by Paula Radcliff of Great Britain.
The 36-year-old Mikitenko surprisingly won the London Marathon last spring in a time of 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games because of what was described as a back injury, but recovered to win in Berlin and in her third marathon ever, she improved her personal best by almost five minutes.
She ran the race with a clever, deliberate mind: She let four Ethiopian and Kenyan runners run a great leap and then caught up with them after about 18 1⁄2 miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31 and Helene Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
Pride and the barriers of black life in a segregated city
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of Greater Orlando, miles from all the glitter, noise and vastness, lies a quiet town where the pride and the challenge of African-American life comes alive.
Eatonville, the first all-black town incorporated in the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is not quite as simple as she described it in 1935: "a town of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown leather, three hundred swimmers, enough quayava, two schools, and no prison".
It's a pilgrimage site now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Eatonville Zora! Festival to pay tribute to Hurston, the most celebrated female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The town she described remains a bystander, even though she made it a tourist stop by including it in a Florida travel guide created by the Federal Writers Project during the Depression.
It's still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their true feelings with the white man, who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing".
Even in the year that Black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open debate on race, many residents remain wary of outsiders' views.
"We pay great attention to how our story is told", says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, a lifelong resident and the oldest member of the parish in the city.
"It has to be right".
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It's both a historic model of black uplift, and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It's a center of literature, but it's also a shadowy example of Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes lauded - that grew out of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the natives are both proud and protective.
And the worry of the Eatonville idea really started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt, rhyming books like "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of Florida's tourist guidebook have turned the town a little bit into Route 17, which leads through the often-overlooked center of Florida, a stage for black history and human drama.
With a big-drum burst into life and literature, Hurston introduced readers to the store of former Eatonville mayor Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"Left of the road", she wrote, "is a white-and-brown, modern, national school with well-kept yards and playgrounds, always looked after by Howard Miller, even though he can't read or write very well".
She also mentioned the widow Dash's new husband, writing that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything that fits in a clock hotel".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
This was clearly not a typical Fodor's publishing house.
It wasn't really a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora told it like it was", says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls Hurston immortalized by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it", she added.
Hurston is still remembered as a chipmunk who came back often after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-year-old Augustus Franklin recalls that most of the time she arrived in town, she arrived unannounced in a big Chevy, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still prides itself on its dress code.
Most of the people were fascinated, Franklin said, but many were squeamish.
"The people of the Dawn have always loved to see", said Franklin.
But, he added, rocking on a back porch chair overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
It seemed that Eatonville had forgotten her along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings at Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood her message or her meaning to the world", said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography, "Wrapped in Rainbows".
The change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to make a five-lane highway through the city instead of Kennedy Boulevard, the local two-lane highway.
The Orlando eruption has already forced Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The design came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in history.
Forced integration, among other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950's, the struggle for racial mixing brought hatred to the very edge of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came and threw oranges and things at people who were sitting on the side", Franklin said.
"We actually had a lady killed by it.
They threw a watermelon from the car".
Writing in The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration and declared its decision in Brown v. Board of Education to be "offensive rather than celebratory to my race".
Residents now claim that desegregation of schools, while positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the local youth.
"Black kids were used to hugging - I remember it - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening", said N.Y. Nathuri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until the teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
"You don't hug your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there's a cultural barrier", Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped to create space for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with a reckless self-confidence and quotes like "How can anyone deny themselves the pleasure of my presence!
I don't know what that means".
In 1975, Alice Walker reached Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight for her reputation to be revived.
Five years later, a highly praised biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway appeared on the shelves of bookstores, re-establishing her in the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville's most famous daughter was re-discovering the lights of the ramp.
Her former neighbors, the Hurstons, now considered her a savior.
To show what could be done to destroy their highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived for the inaugural event two years later, and each January many return to celebrate.
The state backed out of the highway project after several years.
"Those five streams of the highway have raised, you could say, exploded, real civic pride", Nathiriva said.
Boyd said it more simply, "Dawn saved Eatonville".
The victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started attending the local church in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new single-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes seem like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today, it is 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come to seek the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Most interviews require prior permission, and certain things - such as the murals in Eatonville's oldest church, painted by whites and depicting blacks in fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a bold, confident teacher who loves the red meat, still fear that their isolated community will not be understood.
And as the Hurston festival grew, so did domestic pride.
Young people especially are eager to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, troubled and so on, but no better, no worse and just as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, has a sincere love of the community in his voice as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in local government or the police, which he says would benefit from some help.
And even younger ones, such as the 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, just passing by, think, 'Hm, this town is nothing compared to the others,'" said Alondra Kenon recently after church on Sunday.
"But if you really stop and look at the history for a moment, it's a very nice town".
Here in New York , we all speak fluent financial
Nothing has changed at first glance.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and the giant TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn't realize they were in the middle of a storm.
They would never guess that in the glass beehive of offices above their heads, every day the bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York have the worst "bad day at the office" since the 1929 crash.
The messengers are still rattling metal carts down the sidewalks, carrying bagels of muffins to breakfast meetings.
Hispanics still move between the towers and wear, like human mules, fifty-fifty ironed shirts that hang from the railings on their backs.
Office rats are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at the street food stalls, and there's still no yellow cab available on weekdays between 4 and 7 p.m.
It didn't seem like a crisis at all, until, with all the talk about pessimism, I decided to open a savings account on a Thursday afternoon.
Even though I timed this assignment to take a late-afternoon nap at my local JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about 20 people in line.
Not at the cash registers to pick up or deposit cash, but at the front desk, where senior clients order checkbooks, tourists ask directions to Macy's department store, and new customers open accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker", came for the same reason I did.
But unlike me, they've already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in places they came from, like New Jersey, Pennsylvania, or Staten Island.
They have taken money from so-called thrives, money clubs, and those types of thrift shops that operate in only one state and claim to care for their customers like a family.
Fifteen such banks have quietly failed in the past year.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and as New Yorkers were heading home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, was trying to find a bailout buyer.
The office workers and the businesses that stood before me, fearful of another collapse, were moving their cash to the bank that is perceived as a safe haven and that does most of the bailing on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned a lot about finance in the last week.
Some woman at my local Chinese supermarket was on the phone talking to Lehman Borthers, that failed bank, and its emaciated top executive Dick Fuld with as much familiarity as if she were gossiping about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed, 50-something housekeeper of my apartment, changed the subject of our usual conversation - Brad, Angelina, or my food delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she said to me, "I have my savings in money market funds.
I've moved it, I won't risk it".
Muslim graves desecrated after Austrian right-wing crackdown
Heinz-Christian Strache, left, from the Austrian right-wing party of the Free and Filip Dewinter from the Belgian right-wing party of the Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration to present the organisation "Cities against Islamisation" in Antwerp on Thursday 17 January 2008.
They carry signs similar to road signs that depict mosques with a red line crossed out.
Police are accusing right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend that far-right parties made huge gains in the general election.
More than 90 graves in a cemetery in the town of Traun near Linz were badly desecrated sometime between Friday evening and this morning, and police believe it was an organized act.
The perpetrators sprayed some of the graves with Jewish symbols, such as the Star of David, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to cover up the motives of extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It's unclear if this incident was connected in any way to the election.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the reports of the desecration, which came as the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan was coming to an end.
Austria, meanwhile, is entering a soul-searching cycle after swinging to the right in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
Both far-right parties, which together won more than 30 percent of the vote, the Free Party and the Future Alliance of Austria, have waged a vehement anti-immigration campaign and some of their slogans have been condemned as xenophobic by critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Free Party, which won over 18 percent of the vote, protested against headscarves and burqas in the campaign, and even expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived to be Islamic.
At his last meeting with the electors in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both parties are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses carried out immediately after the elections, which put the far right in the position of the strongest political bloc in the country, suggest that this change was caused primarily by young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is not allowed to go on a trip across the border.
Gary Glitter, a glam rock star convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned from traveling to France and Spain.
Officials imposed this six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the monitoring authorities that he planned to travel through France to Spain.
Kent police were granted the travel ban last Thursday after they provided evidence to officials about Glitter's past convictions for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, whose real name is Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford Lower Criminal Court in Kent, but was represented by the lawyers of Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the Judiciary said: "On Thursday, September 25, at the Ashford Criminal Court, the Kent Police asked for an order preventing Mr. Paul Gadd from crossing the border into France and Spain until March 25.
Paul Gadd was not personally present".
Glitter, 64, informed authorities he wanted to travel abroad, as he has a record on the sex offender registry.
They have to notify the authorities if they want to travel abroad for more than three days.
He must also give the police a week's notice of his planned departure.
If he failed to inform the authorities, he could be sentenced to five years.
Kent police have announced that they will not be investigating individual cases of Glitter's possible travels around the county.
A spokesman for the Kent Police said: "The Kent Police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
From our point of view, it's easier to track someone who stays in Britain because we have extensive systems here that deal with potential threats more efficiently.
Protecting the people of Kent is a top priority for Kent Police and we are working diligently to monitor the behaviour of registered sex offenders to minimise any danger to the public".
Glitter returned to Britain last month after serving 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for molesting two girls aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, he flew to Bangkok, where he was to board a flight to London.
But he said he wasn't feeling well, and refused to fly to London.
Thai authorities refused to let him pass passport control and he eventually flew to Hong Kong.
Chinese authorities also refused to allow him to enter, and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and immigration officials insisted he return to Britain.
On 22 August, he finally arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 and remained there while his solicitor David Corker went to the Uxbridge Lower Criminal Court in west London and simultaneously successfully applied for a warrant from Scotland Yard requiring him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter was previously jailed for four months in the United Kingdom for possession of child pornography.
A source from the Home Office said Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, was relieved and happy that Glitter had been prevented from travelling to France and Spain.
"To capture the real character, I photograph the master behind the scenes".
No heels, no calls or costumes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, detached from the focus on the interpretation - only so I achieve the free expression of a man or a woman.
On the one hand, an artist.
On the other, a human.
The inseparable, if not the private, in those moments far from the public - then one can see the familiar gesture, the depth of the casually captured gaze or the passionate gesture of the hands that are carefree because they are not about to step on the stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-people" alternates the theatrical performance with singers, dancers and guitarists with that lesser known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer assembles a unique flamenco iconography from different backgrounds.
The exhibition, which is part of the Flamenco Photography Month (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca) program, "reflects the ever-growing international importance of flamenco", says the author, explaining that the "Flamenco-people" "can be any people, but when you look at the photographs, you will see that they are not typical images of the artists on stage.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists able to bring passion, sadness, joy... onto the stage and captivate the audience completely.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to take a photograph on stage.
They carry their personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the great flamenco.
Enchanted by the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey of portraying flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on the camera of the board.
They are portraits that, because of the choice of camera and material, resemble classic photography.
The use of different stylistic means is contrary to the classical basis of the film and lends it a contemporary spirit, an idea that, according to Bauer himself, mirrors flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, but which never ceases to surprise and evolve".
What draws the audience is not the performance of the dance, the singing, or the play itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment in which we meet the most essential, the spirit that is revealed in the way we perceive, be and experience, this was and is the constant of the work presented during these days in the gallery El Fotómata.
This selection of almost seventy photographed artists is made up of famous flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo, among others.
The project has become a sort of anthology of flamenco and will soon be published in a book, which will include the exhibited portraits.
Two years ago, Bauer's passion for portraiture led him to the idea of doing a retrospective of the "SportART project".
Although their concept is different from that of the "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "to photograph people, to get to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a moment, whether long or short, is my passion.
I think the portrait is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or encounter people, personalities, who sometimes you don't even know, or they give you a few minutes to take a picture.
Despite such circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas".
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people", is on display in the El Fotómata Gallery in the street de la Mata 20, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
Vargas Llosa admitted that the novel he's writing is "audacious"
It is set in an environment he is not familiar with, and tells of events unknown to him, but Mario Vargas Llosa is going to succeed in his new project - he is currently working on a novel whose protagonist is Roger Casemant, an Irish nationalist who lived for twenty years in the Congo and travelled in the Amazon.
The perennial favorite for the Nobel Prize in Literature, admitted yesterday at the Hay Festival Segovia that the project he is currently engaged in is "a boldness" and that "everything suggests that I shouldn't be writing" this novel.
"If I had my wits about me, I wouldn't do it, but I will do it and I believe I will finish it", concluded his speech at the festival of exchange of ideas, thoughts and words, which over four days saw hundreds of writers, historians and journalists and thousands of other people gather in the city of Aquatucta.
The author of the novel "The City and the Dogs" was one of the main characters of the third year of the festival of words and fulfilled expectations.
Vargas Llosa, who won the Hay Festival's prize for favorite writer - an old edition of Dickens' "Our mutual friend" - filled the Juan Bravo theater to the last.
With Felix Rome, who introduced him, he had a devoted audience before him, to whom the hour passed like water - the Peruvian with astonishing accuracy and a noteworthy dose of humor recalled how he had grown from an original "incredible adventure" to a "pleasure of a passionate reader" and "the power to live more than I have lived" a literary mission; how he supplies the "lack of inspiration" by writing "disciplinedly", carefully arranging, editing and rewriting the text; or how his writing was influenced by Alexandre Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Dumas and what "memorial images" are the basic backbone of his stories.
The Spanish-American novelist admitted that "there is no way" to determine whether or to what extent books can change lives, "but I refuse to believe that literature is just entertainment, a fleeting experience" - Vargas Llosa emphasized, saying that it "acted on people" and "tended to try to get out of line", and called on writers to "not succumb to frivolity" and "take responsibility" for their mission.
