Actress Heather Locklear arrested for driving under the influence of drugs.
Actress Heather Locklear, the beloved Amanda of Melrose Place, was arrested this weekend in Santa Barbara, California, for driving under the influence of drugs.
A witness saw her perform unusual maneuvers while trying to get out of a parking lot in Montecito, a spokesman for the California Highway Patrol told People magazine.
The witness said that at about 4:30 p.m., Locklear "screwed the accelerator, slid back and forth in the noise, and tried to get out of the parking lot - overturning her sunglasses several times".
A witness who apparently didn't recognize the actress at first saw Locklear a moment later pulling over on a nearby highway and getting out of the vehicle.
The person also alerted the emergency services because "he feared for Locklear's life".
When a police patrol arrived, they found the actress inside a vehicle that had partially blocked the road.
"She appeared to be disoriented", and so the officers took her to a specialized drug and alcohol testing center.
A police spokesman said the actress cooperated and alcohol abuse was ruled out immediately, but "we believe Locklear was under the influence of some medication, which was apparent to the officers at first glance".
Locklear was arrested on suspicion of driving under the influence of an unspecified substance and taken into custody at around 7pm, although she was released a few hours later.
Two months ago, Locklear returned from a treatment clinic where she was recovering from anxiety and depression.
Llamazares urges the Andalusian IU to exercise its powers in the Silva case
The general director of the IU and United Left MP Gaspar Llamazares said today that the final decision in the case of the former Seville Youth and Sports Council member Francisco Manuela Silvy, who resigned last week after being accused of acting in favor of his family, will depend on the regional party association.
"I'm too federalist for that, it's up to the Andalusian organization to exercise its powers", Llamazares suggested in a speech to which the party will have to step in relation to a former Seville city council member.
However, the head of the IU insisted that "transparency" was absolutely necessary in the case of investigations into the illegal acts committed by Silva: "The IU has always fought for the maximum transparency in such matters".
He also stressed that the party has a "strict code of ethics for all public functions".
"Flower blood", the epic wager of Garcia
Inspired by Benito Pérez Galdós' Episodes from the National Past, José Luis Garci's film "Blood of May" (Sangre de mayo) recreates the famous Spanish uprising against the French - the most ambitious film in his filmography, with a budget of around 15 million euros.
In this way, the filmmaker wanted to "draw on the eloquence of the characters and the analysis of society" that he had always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today, together with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría, during the presentation of the film to a large team of interpreters.
Blood Flower with a running time of two and a half hours will be released in cinemas this Friday and in the future there are more than four hours of series for Telemadrid TV.
As a great admirer of the literary work of Galdós, José Luis Garci claims that by making this film he has fulfilled his "childhood dream", which he owes to Esperanza Aguirre, who commissioned him three years ago for the Autonomous Province of Madrid to film the bicentennial of Madrid on May 2, he accepted the offer with the fact that the plot would be based on Episodios del pasado nacional.
The 15 million budget, which was entirely contributed by the Madrid province, represents a "unique opportunity" for García to create an environment with backdrops and costumes that match the image of "a crumbling Spain that had been wrong in the leader it was worth fighting for - the struggle for independence under Ferdinand VII. led to the decline and backwardness of the country", he said.
The director regrets, however, that he cannot count on the financial support that was given to the films Ala triste (The Sad Wing) or Goya's Ghosts - almost twice the amount of La Sangre de flores (The Blood of Flowers) - so he could not shoot some scenes from a script signed at the same time by Horacio Valcárcel, with whom he works almost throughout his film career.
The director of the film Volver a empezar works as he is accustomed to - on the stage with actors with whom he usually rehearses before filming and who he does not cast because he finds it "humiliating" and also believes that "part of the director's job is to go to theatres and cinemas and find out what is going on in the craft he is involved in".
Many of the actors he has chosen for May's Blood have appeared in front of his camera several times, such as Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Garcia, who has four Oscar nominations, one of which he won, believes that none of the three candidates representing Spain this year before the Hollywood Academy, the "July Blood", the "Seven Tables of the French Billiards" and the last one chosen, "Blind Sunflowers", represent the young generation of the Spanish film scene, but he claims that "they will appear".
Garci's not going to get any awards for this movie.
"At first you think you're working for what's next, but then you realize you're only working for the money, and you're willing to make one more movie", explains Garci, who has been directing for more than 30 years.
Isabel Bayón brings to life the spiritual legacy of the Sevillian dancer Tortola Valencia
The Seville flamenco dancer will pay tribute to another Seville dancer.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia, whose father was Catalan (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and mother was Andalusca (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the district of Triana, and when she was three years old, they moved with their family to London.
She was a modern dancer and specialized in oriental dances.
She lived a passionate life, she was a pioneer of women's emancipation like Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and a vegetarian, and fought for the abolition of the corset, which prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, influenced by the dance and aesthetic revolution of interwar Europe, was enriched by Isabelle Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Peppa Gamboa and she suggested this character to me - it seemed incredible".
According to the dancer, "it's not about telling her life, it's about capturing the soul.
The titles of her dances reminded me of the rhythms of flamenco.
So I think "butterfly dance" was a guajiro or "snake dance" was a tango.
Her dance was sensual and I was told that my dance was also in keeping with this aesthetic", he says.
The performance will feature two exceptional personalities: Miguel Veda, who will sing Isabella in one performance as in "La puerta abierta" (The Open Door), and the dance teacher Matilde Coral, who made an exception and agreed to collaborate with her former pupil.
"Matilde represents the elder Tortola, a mature character.
I'm happy that she accepted the offer to be part of my project, and it's a great honor for me".
The performance also features music and guitars by Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with vocals by Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; drums by El Pájara, viola by Rafa El Viola and the collaboration of actor Juanfry Juárez, "who plays the role of the eternal guide of this kind of artist who are primadones with everything, and who are always in love with them".
The play also takes into account the life of this woman, who was in her time in such distant places as India, the United States or Russia, and also throughout Europe, because she usually stayed in London.
"I wanted to remember her because I think she was one of those women who had a huge influence at a certain time, but no one knows her today, and even less appreciates her work", says Bayón.
The show starts at 8.30 tonight at the Lope de Vega Theatre.
The book "The Diary of a Newly Married Man" concludes the triennial
The presentation of the first illustrated edition of the "Diary of the Newlyweds" in Saint Stephen's Church (New York), the place where Juan Ramón Jiménez married Zenobia in March 1916, is part of the programme coordinated by the Cultural Council of the Autonomous Government of Andalusia to celebrate the "Triennial of Zenobia and Juan Ramón" (2006-2008), organised to celebrate the fiftieth anniversary of the award of the Nobel Prize in Literature and the anniversary of their death.
The "Triennale of Zenobia and Juan Ramón" is drawing to a close with a new edition of this work, an international congress to be held in New York, the renovation of the Nobel Museum House, and the traveling exhibition "Juan Ramón Jiménez: A Ray of Sunshine", which opened in May of this year and, after touring various Andalusian provinces, is scheduled to move to New York in time for the congress.
The Cultural Council of the Autonomous Government of Andalusia has also ordered eight hundred copies of "Diary of a Newly Married Man", edited by Pedro Tabernero and illustrated by Jacob Pérez-Encis, to continue spreading awareness about the personality and work of one of the most prominent Andalusian poets.
