Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will have to install an "alcolock"
The Department of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for drunk driving must install a system in his car that prevents him from starting the car while drunk or if he is not breathing.
The proposal was announced in June this year and is now included in the annual report of the Office of the Prosecutor General, which states that it is a pilot project that will last for one year.
The aim is to put drivers back behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to undergo a course of traffic re-education.
The experience will be shared by the National Transport Safety Authority, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Technological Institute for Automobile Safety (FITSA).
Statistics show that between 30 and 75 percent of drivers charged with more than one DUI will re-enter the DUI.
Alcolock should prevent this, as it is a system attached to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe before or if a higher than permitted alcohol concentration is recorded.
It costs more than €1,000 and would have to be paid by the offender.
A study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that, in the first year of implementation, the number of overtaking was reduced by 65% in vehicles equipped with this device.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate its implementation, since the legal adjustment can be done in the usual way, the necessary adjustment of the penal provisions requires a change of the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial version, although it has already been installed on a trial basis in some industrial and public utility vehicles.
The Congress of Deputies will vote tomorrow on a proposal by the PSOE (Spanish Socialist Workers' Party) which recommends installing this system in school buses, as is the case in France.
