Speaking in Your Sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don't mean the ones that wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but the ones that talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it might scare you, but it's actually meaningless.
It's a harmless sleep disorder called somniloquio.
It's quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure some of you have heard him talk in his sleep.
This phenomenon may occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with high fevers) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There's no one reason that would explain her attack.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night-time rabies, nocturnal enuresis (night wetting), or somnambulism, but not necessarily.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stressful or exasperating situations.
In any case, it's a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears varies as well.
A child may speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches, etc.).
In cases where it is strong, it would be appropriate to observe the child and consult a professional to see if there is a problem that is causing great anxiety and manifesting in this way.
We said it's a benign disorder, so it's not treated unless it's combined with another sleep disorder that can be treated (such as when it's associated with apnea syndrome or with chronic stress).
But we can do so by keeping in mind some very simple precautions, such as:
Try not to disturb the child too much before he goes to bed.
So seek out quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who are hard to get along with, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain a measure of inner calm.
It will help the baby sleep better.
If you experience somnolence, try to remain calm.
Remind yourself that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Helpful Counsel
Don't be him.
It's useless because he's not conscious and you're interrupting his sleep.
Even if he talks, he sleeps, and therefore rests.
Remember that if you notice that he seems to be very anxious in a succession of occasions, it would be a good idea to seek advice or to find out what is causing the child to be so anxious.
If he is able to understand what you are saying (which is not usually the case), avoid the temptation to question him and extract information from him.
It won't do any good, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious enough to organize his thoughts.
Moreover, you may hear what he says but you do not know what he is dreaming and why he is saying it, so be very careful how you interpret the information and draw your conclusions.
Never tell a child that you can ask him his secrets at night.
Not even for fun.
It's a very anxious situation.
Don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's just an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
