Interview - Blood that is Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly delighted, as Héma-Québec has become one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he has regained the public's trust, which was badly shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well-known, the national blood bank administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Board was contaminated with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In view of this drama and the outcry of the public, in February 1994 the Canadian government launched a public inquiry, presided over by Judge Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations to ensure that such a disaster never happened again.
While Judge Krever was delaying the report, some provinces started a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee took over this role.
According to the report by Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, to supply Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Company to supply all provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in the Québec blood system", recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was dismal.
"We have been working on this issue for a number of years, and we have been working on it for a number of years", he says, adding with pride that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population had trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary does not overlook the fact that "trust is a very fragile thing".
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
"We were seeing a lot of cases of human-type mad cow disease in Europe at the time, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease", says the woman who has been running the company since its inception in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could be spread through blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, namely that in the event of unknown and potentially serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, characterised by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, exclusionary measures should be taken.
So in April 1999 we refused blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Then, a few years ago, it was safely proven that the disease is transmitted through blood.
So this episode showed us that the precautionary principle made sense".
In 1999, a more accurate technique for detecting HIV came on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which detect the presence of the virus itself in donor blood, rather than the presence of antibodies on which previous tests were based.
NAT has helped to shorten the silent period between the moment a patient is infected and the moment our techniques can detect the first viruses in the blood, she explains.
We've managed to shorten that period to less than a week.
We have substantially reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without us knowing and without us being able to detect it.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of acquiring AIDS through blood transfusion.
The risk of receiving blood contaminated with HIV is now one in 12 million.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone becomes infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission via a blood product is reported.
I believe that today we can receive or prescribe the blood transfusion needed to heal without any fear", says the head of Héma-Québec.
"The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what pathogenic element might be in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus, which is transmitted through the blood by insect bites, was discovered on the island of Réunion.
"We must always be vigilant", continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also be able to count on sufficient supplies.
"The needs are growing because the population is aging.
Because of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of eligible Quebecers".
Any healthy person at least 18 years of age, meeting the eligibility criteria, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who donate blood are rejected because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they've visited a country where mud fever is rampant, they're excluded for a year.
"With that 3%, we can maintain a level that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, the donors in the network should be replenished in proportion to their age and their inability to donate blood.
But getting people to donate blood is a challenge, especially when it comes to keeping people motivated to become regular donors.
Life is so unrestrained today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood", laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively for major burns.
The tissue is analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also operates the only public cord blood bank in Québec.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth cord blood sample into the bank, and we anticipate receiving over a thousand a year.
Early next year, we should start offering them for transplants", says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some moms are disappointed that they don't have access to it", because Héma-Québec doesn't have enough funds to offer this complex and expensive program to all Quebec hospitals.
