Opinions - Orwellian discourse by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched a lawsuit against three authors and a poor small publishing house for libel in an attempt to provoke a "transparent public debate" and demands six million.
If it's true that judges are independent and impartial, they don't judge truth, especially in cases of defamation, but the law.
Not surprisingly, Garver completely ignores this fundamental distinction.
Or is the best way for Barrick Gold to conduct public debate to bankrupt anyone who dares to take the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada will be forced to spend a considerable sum to prepare themselves to defend and fight in a very unequal battle with an army of lawyers backed by the almost limitless pockets of the mining community.
The tactics in these unresolved battles often consist in ruining the defendants in order to promote a settlement that will silence the other party and, in addition, will scare anyone who dares to pursue the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of the whole thing to the public.
Contrary to what happens in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate is normally about the exchange of ideas, not the whipping.
So what the mining companies had to do was open up their books, open up their documentation, and start a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and funding independent scientific teams that could shed some light on the whole thing.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no faith in public opinion and has been quietly rejecting petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand "public debate" while at the same time disdaining the opinions of the public?
It seems that in the vice president's world, that word means only the fat-paid lawyers, not all Canadians; that's a pretty narrow definition of the term.
In a democracy, even the most violent people have a say.
Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - that the public who supports Noir Canada authors and publishers do so primarily because they reject the brutal ways of the mining community.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and consider the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant is to be gagged (in its prosecution of "public debate", Barrick, by the way, has just issued an official appeal to the authors of Noir Canada to officially inform them that they should stop using the term...).
Barring Garver's surreal speech, the prosecution of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university's freedom of inquiry and the pursuit of truth, which is essential to any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are not to the liking of the rich corporations of this world without being subjected to repeated prosecution, who else can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have been created by following the scientific standards that Noir Canada's authors enjoy.
He has a right to an answer.
The university environment that we belong to has long been able to manage debate and disagreement and resolve conflict.
Barrick Gold's exaggerated lawsuit clearly shows that despite what it claims, it has no desire to have a transparent debate.
It's a loss to the academic world, as well as to the public debate in Canada, and it's time for governments to put in place measures to curb this type of unwarranted prosecution.
