His Republican opponent, John McCain, asked by another station whether he would vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope I will".
"The rough outlines I've read [suggest] that this is something we're all going to have to digest and move on to.
"It is simply unacceptable to choose to be inactive", he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to use taxpayer money to buy up the bad loans and risky and unsellable assets of American financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages, then spread to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA), and resulted in cash freezes and the dissolution of banks and financial institutions.
The failure of the first draft of the agreement last week is the fault of the Republican members of the House.
Since Democrats have agreed that some "toxic" assets of troubled companies will only be guaranteed by the government, not redeemed, the belief that the impasse is inevitable has been perpetuated.
In an effort to reconcile the conflicting views in Congress, a provision was added that the government would be able to introduce new fees to help it recover its deposit if it had to absorb losses for five years as a result of the program.
The new plan calls for an initial deposit of $250 billion, with the possibility of adding another $100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The $350 billion in additional funding is due to be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for its help, Washington will receive shares in the salvaged companies, which will pay dividends if it makes a profit and which it can sell back when it's all gone.
The Federal Government will be able to delay foreclosure proceedings on the properties associated with the loans covered by the plan, as well as set limits on the amount of assessments and compensation paid to executives of affected companies.
The plan's backers would like to put it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts, it's not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Because yesterday, there were still voices against this project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It's clear that Washington is not listening", said Scott Garrett, a Republican on the House Finance Committee, addressing voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
Making money off of the taxpayers is not the answer".
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed the "Skeptics Committee", presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred esteemed economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us: we ask Congress to take its time and consider carefully what course to take", he said yesterday.
At the same time, Europe was once again being told that this crisis was a world crisis.
After the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (USD 16.3 billion).
The intervention of the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from its bid to buy its rival, which has been on the verge of collapse since losing €2 billion (USD 2.9 billion) in the wake of the US mortgage crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest banks in Europe and one of the 10 largest insurance companies.
"We will not lose this money", Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos declared yesterday.
"In return, we get voting rights in the bank and influence.
And that is what caretakers and households can appreciate in these uncertain times".
On the other side of the Channel, the British government has yet to begin to nationalise another bank hit by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) were loans for property purchases.
According to yesterday's announcement, the Spanish bank Santander is buying out branches and accounts of British bank clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government has had to nationalize since the financial crisis began.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a socially committed icon
His azure-eyed beauty has long been his trump card, others say his weakness.
Has this American actor with a charming smile gotten over his narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity and enduring talent that he possessed also kept him away from the power category that breeds true stars.
Yet, what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died Friday at the age of 83 at his ranch in Connecticut from lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the bold years of American cinema.
Less grandiose than Brando, to whom he was similar and long a rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was of Hungarian descent.
From these European roots, one of the famous faces of the American dream was born.
Without the egos, which is the last sign of quality.
Because in him, this whole country was in love with a self-made man, a veteran of the war in the Pacific, wounded in battle, who in the early 1950s studied acting at Yale, then attended the Actor's Studio in New York and celebrated triumphs in theater, television and soon in film.
The same civil rights activist was also a race car driver, a runner-up in the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans, and a sex symbol, despite having been a model partner of actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With it, too, go the shadowy places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the noise of show business itself, which will forever remain somewhat mysterious.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
The departure of Paul Newman this weekend has left movie lovers dizzy as his big roles compete on the black screen of remembrance.
He's followed by more than half a century of the ever-changing American seventh art.
The charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in A Streetcar Named Desire, a 1958 Tennessee Williams adaptation, is reborn.
From a more recent past, we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that failed to meet all expectations.
So many more Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, the bullied, violent, unforgettable delinquent from Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role intended for James Dean, taken over after his death, which in 1956 brought Newman into the limelight.
The sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, the Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
The bitter and vindictive pool player in Robert Ross's brilliant The Hustler (1961), the same character he plays in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earns him his only Oscar nomination in 1987 out of seven.
This face of the wandering ages, it was he.
And him again.
His career has been marked by a series of eras.
He is best known to young audiences for his role as Reggie Dunlop, a non-traditional hockey coach, in the cult film Slap Shot George Roye Hill (1977).
Fans saw him again in 1994 in The Coen Brothers' Hudsucker Proxy.
He closed his career with the role of the Irish mob godfather in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003.
Unlike some movie legends who left the industry relatively soon, Newman stayed in the business for a long time, even though he decried Hollywood for its pomp, ostentation and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier, not without humour, considered it "a living challenge to underplay", judging that in his performances he had pushed too hard on the saw.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, whose roles came as a delicacy, the profession was not always so tender.
But he played first lovers less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, bums, and hopelessness, whose decay and rebellion were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed a little-known side of his shy sensibility.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, gives a sensitive portrait of a woman full of melancholy.
To his son Scott, who he lost to an overdose, he dedicated the 1984 film Harry and Son, a work of shame and sorrow.
In a tribute to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade Robert Redford (their co-star in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) sadly declared, "His presence has made my life and this country better".
Generosity, love of life, these are the main qualities of a dead actor.
Leaving behind his legendary career, also leaves a great fighter for civil rights, ecology, independent film, and the decline of Hollywood.
We were used to seeing his likeness on bottles of vinegar, on sauces, on biscuits and other foods, which might have seemed rather distasteful, although at first it was a gag.
However, the profits from the sale went into his Foundation for Troubled Childhood's account.
So, rather than be lulled by fame, Newman engaged in society until the last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters, which included these words: "Your father was forever and to the end grateful to his lucky planet.
It was an honor to be here".
And we were honored to follow the career of such a visionary and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, a model citizen.
What was produced in the Zuschlag & Co. Factory?
Soon, on October 8, the trial will begin in the criminal case against János Zuschlag and his associates.
The politician and his associates are charged with fraud, perpetrated by a long-standing and systematic criminal organisation, which has caused extreme damage, in addition to other offences, including forgery of documents.
According to the prosecutor's office, they used the money received in public tenders for their own purposes and often documented the completion of tasks with fictitious invoices.
The money from the state and local governments - a total of approximately 65 million forints - went partly to the treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The method also reported by the investigating authority was that the money received in public tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no real consideration and the commitments undertaken by the association were never received.
According to the prosecution, a large portion of the invoices were fake.
The forms for these invoices were from the Josefváros market, the round stamp was made in Kiskunhalasi.
The names of the companies to be used for the invoices were decided, among other things, on the ring road along the northern shore of Balaton, which was sent by István Ladose to János Zuschlag.
According to his statement, the first named was supposed to look for pensions and restaurants.
In these he requested accounts for his consumption, the model of which was then used to produce invoices submitted in the context of public tenders drawn up by, inter alia, the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs, and the Municipality of the Capital.
The invoices were mostly issued by István Lados and his associate András Őrim, who, according to our information, wrote the reports most often needed to obtain subsidies.
During his "study tour", Lados had a look at a cellar.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and its associates in 2003, the hotel catered for a 90-strong group from the Insurance Pont group.
But the company executive said that this number of people would not have been able to fit into the facility all at once.
Similarly, the invoices issued in the summer of 2002 by the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért, were full of formal and substantive errors.
The guesthouse in Badacsonytomaji had only three rooms, and no more than ten people could sleep there in one night, yet the bill listed one hundred and thirty guests.
However, the imaginative compilers of the forms went too far when they referred to the company Pigal s. r. o., which also provides hospitality services, and whose accounts, according to the information provided to the public prosecutor's office, did not even include documents bearing the names of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
The company's CEO, Győző Farkas, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he knew immediately that the documents were fake.
"The name of our company and our tax number were on the stamp in the wrong place".
He added that apart from the formalities, the fact that they accommodated 100 people according to the invoice did not agree, as they only have 11 rooms, which do not have such a large capacity.
Plus, the bill also listed the food, and their restaurant has been out of business for a long time.
The eager invoice makers were not convinced that the well-known Budapest travel agency only organised international trips, and they foolishly listed the cash-on-delivery invoice as a service for arranging a trip to Hungary, which was also not in line with the company's billing practice.
Moreover, as it emerged during the investigation, VAT was also mentioned in the document, even though the organisation of trips to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
Four documents issued to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation by Hotel Révfülöp s. r. o. did not agree, inter alia, to the amount of VAT, since the company's activities were not subject to the 25% VAT rate but to the 15% VAT rate, and the staff of the hotel issued only printed invoices, but the invoice was handwritten.
Moreover, the 'issuers' distorted the invoice, for example by indicating that one company, as revealed by the public prosecutor's office, carried out road freight transport activities which were not carried out by the company originally established as investment consultancy.
The fact that the invoices issued to the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért Foundation and the XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont associations were false was also due to formal discrepancies - the incorrect invoice format and the incorrect stamp.
As in the case of Ravenna k. s. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied that they had issued the invoices.
For example, the forgers did not even notice that HIB s. r. o. from Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time (2001) when the group from Fiatal Városért was feeding at its premises, which is why, according to our information, the liquidation commissioner of the company also denied that he had issued the paper.
They were making the invoices deliberately.
The second group of invoicers are those who knew they were to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Esély Budapestért foundation has issued bills for approximately four million forints to the Harmadik Évezredért foundation at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták.
The head of Collab s.r.o. was allegedly coerced into issuing a fictitious account by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Zuschlag and his associates were also cooperating with Biogate s.r.o., currently in liquidation, which in 2003 had invoiced the Jobb Jövőért Foundation and the Atlasz and Vörösfenyő associations for approximately HUF 5 million, which was not followed by any real economic activity.
Nor was there any movement of money, because the invoices created were later cancelled, which the organizations had forgotten to mention in their documents.
The next group of invoicing companies includes those that had ties to the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the representative of the Ukrainian manager of Delta Trió s.r.o., a company dealing with fuel and motor vehicles, based in Budapest, but which is not listed on the company's website.
The company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment in October, November and December 2005 for a total value of approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the information obtained during the investigation, these invoices were bought by the Kiskunhalas company Cash Investment s. r. o., which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The manager of this company was a man from Romania, to whom documents related to the same company were handed over by Iván Kubatov between 2002 and 2005.
As we know, during the investigation Kubatov admitted that he had issued invoices on behalf of the company to Atlasz, Hoppá and the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért foundations and had himself received their consideration.
Expressly at the request of Ivan Kubatov, Fa-Bani Jos Faipari s.r.o. and Jos-Investment k.s. were founded by Romanian masons.
But in fact, none of the firms were operating, according to the defendant, because they were not given jobs.
However, the undertakings were in his favour, since, at the request of his co-accused lawyer, Zsolt Szente, who also drew up the articles of incorporation, he issued invoices on behalf of the undertakings to the associations Atlasz and Y-Generation, which were affiliated to Zuschlag.
On behalf of Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov has issued 15 invoices to organisations totalling HUF 14,2 million.
The prosecutor's office estimated that Kubatov had gotten 10% of the amounts listed on invoices and VAT.
The man also used Szi-Beri k.t. to issue fictitious invoices, this time for a tendering procedure for Biztos Pont.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség and Modern Magyarországért submitted their bids in January 2006 to the public competition of the Mihálye Táncsicse Foundation (TMA), a public benefit organization of the Socialist Party.
They received 500 000 forints each, but they did not use the sums to achieve the objectives set out in the proposals.
To conceal this, TMA submitted five fictitious invoices from Works Team Ltd.
These invoices were found during a home search in Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
During the trial, some of the defendants will probably describe the process of invoicing, as they have done at the prosecutor's office.
What might be interesting is if the main defendant, János Zuschlag, decides to reveal himself.
His testimony so far is not very detailed, and despite his promises to give a full account on several occasions, he has not done so.
The question is whether it's in his interest - in exchange for paying a large part of the damage, fifty million forints, maybe the socialists have made a deal with him and Zusi will take it on himself.
He may have been offended, since his requests for a reduction in the terms of his detention, namely that he be placed under house arrest, have so far remained unheard.
While perpetrators of economic crimes, who have caused far greater damage that has not yet been repaired, can walk around freely or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their homes, he does not have that option.
The psychology of triumph: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neurological and economic underpinnings of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been uncovered by researchers from the departments of neurology and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don't want to be left behind in an eBay auction-type competition, so they're willing to pay a premium.
Research has used experimental auction to try to map the pattern of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a random auction, using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) to examine active areas of the subjects' brains.
In both games, the participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the important element is to beat the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to function intensively when the loser lost.
This area of the brain plays a role in the "self-reward" mechanism of the nervous system, among many other functions.
The price increase can therefore be explained by the researchers' desire to avoid a sharp reaction of the striata.
To support their theory, members of the research team of economists conducted a cross-sectional financial survey.
Three groups bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
Additionally, the other members of the group were promised that if they came out victorious, they would receive an additional $15 in reward.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but if they lost, they lost that money too.
The difference between the two groups was that one group was emphasized as winning and the other as losing.
But the members of the "loser" group were willing to go higher than the control and "winner" group, which confirms the neurologists' hypothesis.
"These results cannot be deduced from any pre-existing economic theory.
They have hitherto explained the phenomena observed in auctions of triumph and risk-averse joy.
It was only when neurological imaging techniques helped us resolve the discrepancy between the two theories that we now arrived at a third explanation", said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's Stern School of Business.
Hepatitis: When Should You See a Doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed as a leading cause of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 of these are treated, the reason being that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are similar, with inflammation of the liver and jaundice being the most common, but the causes and the illness they cause are different.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways, depending on the source: hepatitis A and E through the digestive system (e. g. through contaminated food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretions, saliva).
Travellers should in any case be protected by vaccination against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingesting an infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, and vomiting.
Then, jaundice, lightened stools, and darkened urine form on the skin and whites of the eyes, and the treatment may take two to three weeks.
Each year, a million people worldwide die from the more serious forms of this disease, liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that only about one in ten of those infected are estimated to be medicated.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most people with the disease are unaware of their illness, and the pathogen is secretly destroying liver cells, so that in many cases the first symptoms do not appear for 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention, regular surveillance, is very important.
Three groups have a much higher than average incidence of the disease: people who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
As the disease can be detected by routine laboratory tests, a person should consult his or her doctor if he or she experiences any symptoms of unknown origin.
If detected early, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, and thus prevent infection and cancer.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, which was first celebrated globally by organizations representing patients in 2004.
It aims to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by these viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Who believes in God, doesn't it hurt so much?
Recent research suggests that belief in God acts as a kind of analgesic that may have eased the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment to see how belief in God affects a person's perception of pain, reports Britain's Telegraph newspaper.
In a rather bizarre study, 12 Catholics and an equal number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks while they all looked at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, the Catholic faithful were able to eliminate much of the pain.
The technology that probes the human brain has also shown that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
The research is the first in a series of studies involving academics as well as scientists, philosophers and theologians from various parts of the university.
The test was done precisely by attaching a sparkler to the left arm of the subject, which gave electric shocks.
The researchers asked the subjects to look closely at two paintings: a 17th-century Sassoferrat's Madonna of Mary and a 15th-century painting of Leonardo da Vinci's Lady with the Rosette.
The authors of the study hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would induce a state of piety in the faithful, whereas da Vinci's painting was chosen because it did not differ much from the first and seemed to them to have a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electric shocks in four consecutive sessions, while separately viewing images with religious or general themes.
Catholics reported that they felt "safe" at the sight of the Virgin Mary, as if they were "cared for" and "calmed down, filled with peace".
When they saw a religious painting, they reportedly felt 12 percent less pain than when they saw Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the study, believes that any powerful image can have a similar effect on atheists, provided the right one is found.
"We had to find an image that they would see very positively, from the mother's or the father's point of view", the psychologist said.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results.
"Practice of faith should change and in many cases will change our personality", Wright added.
After such great results, it's only a question of what effect it would have on the pain regulation of the faithful if they were shown some Madonna by Leonardo or a painter of similar calibre.
Would a view of the Virgin Mary's quality produce even better results?
You are what you share
On its tenth birthday, Google can claim that people can find it in their pocket at least as well as they can find it in the sky; they know where they've been on vacation, what kind of medical examinations they're taking, and what they're interested in.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's executives, that's still not enough.
But as for the skeptics, who parallel the Orwellian dark vision, they are not clear about the very nature of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, which is necessary for the Google founders to stick to their original intention, which was: "Let's organize all the information in the world!"
According to a Google representative, after ten years of global work, the company is just beginning to be able to work with all the information.
Asked what he would be doing in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "what should I do tomorrow?" or "what kind of job would I be good for?" - questions that are seemingly simple, but that software won't be able to answer until it knows enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that the exact words searched are captured during an Internet search, as well as the IP address from which the search was made and the pages to which the interested party was redirected.
For example, Personalized Search, launched two years ago, allows users to keep a record of their browsing history, to look back at what they've searched for and clicked on, and in the long run, to generate results that are more personalised - the same logic will be used by Recommendations, which will offer products and services based on the preferences that have been previously mentioned and stored.
What if my data is used against me, what if someone looks at what I do? - users who are afraid of Google's data monopoly ask.
In most cases, the scope of the potential power represented by the company is what is terrifying, and the backlash does not evoke guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion against power in Internet users.
It is, however, a well-established fact that all search terms are not only captured but may also be disclosed to a third party in justified cases, in which case the privacy rights of Internet users are not protected.
Perhaps the most well-known recent example was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that allowed the identification of pedophiles from the Orkut community pages created through it.
But Internet users worried about privacy rights were given a reprieve in May when the company, along with the electronic rights organization EFF, successfully proved its case against the FBI: Google must not be forced by any future article of the Constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(In the same time period, the federal government successfully recovered nearly 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms it had obtained with the help of the years-old Child Protection Act, but was unable to obtain individual user search lists, or complete lists of websites and keywords, spanning a two-month period.)
The view of Google is so contradictory: it is whipped by those who fear the release of their personal data because they feel that their private sphere and private life will be damaged by using Google's services, and they revolt against it like they do with multinational corporations with a conservative image.
And yet the American geek culture and its wild offshoot, gathering around itself computer enthusiasts, activists and users, appearing in many countries, sees in it a new generation of big business, "corporation that now is bustling", unlike its rival Microsoft, considered to be the conqueror of the world because of Windows, however both are fighting for the same goals.
This may be because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require its users to provide an identification code or ask them to pay for its applications; the open, free and always fresh source of information and software packages seem much more accessible, youthful, cooler than the practice of official software.
But it may also be because geeks understand the very problematic relationship between the internet and individual rights that has brought about one of the most talked about keywords of recent years: web 2.0.
Because Web 2.0 is about nothing but collaboration, about intentionally leaving traces behind and using the communication channels that we have, and although the scope of it is different for everyone, the essence is the same: we show up.
The average young person can have a profile on several community sites, from Facebook to Xangu, which can be linked to other services, such as Twitter or the music-tracking application last.fm, which can be linked to navigation systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and a blog where the latest photo galleries of his stored on Flickr or Picasa will be automatically discovered.
But there are plenty of examples where it shines through: a friend in the morning can easily figure out who her drunken boyfriend was with by looking at a flood of photos of mutual friends, or a company can fire an employee just for expressing an honest opinion about top management on its blog: one thing is for sure, the concept of privacy has been completely overhauled today.
The one who lives an online life is made up of what he shows off, so we could define the basic thesis behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who wants to keep something secret or at least avoid Google's monopoly has a chance (starting with Scroogl, which uses Google's search engine but intentionally leaves no traces).
A small number of people, for example, deliberately don't register to community sites so they can't be found. Google's online applications, from text editors to photo editors to news portals, can be replaced by alternative versions that aren't connected to giant server parks and don't provide us with the highest quality profile possible.
Public opinion is waiting in the wings for Google to show its teeth.
With a current value of $156 billion, the company is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion), or Coca Cola ($110 billion), the AdWords/AdSense advertising platforms threaten the investment of advertising agencies, and the services being introduced at an ever-accelerating pace are seriously making life miserable not only for Microsoft but for many other software designers.
But critical observers also find counter-points that are disturbing: for example, the top management completely rejected the protests of employees after doubling the fee for the company's nursery school, and the company's management considered that the daily meals for employees were too expensive, all of which are lost in the fact that Google bowed to the Chinese government in 2006 and, under their agreement, suppressed any discovery that was contrary to good taste or the interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal rules is that it never advertises new services until they are ready to be used, but it is certain that the expected problems of the coming months and years may take the world to new places: while some believe that Google's project of scanning and archiving books and magazines is taking on such a scale that the company will soon have to deal with the US Supreme Court, others are afraid of its Health system, in which we can compile a complete health profile with previous searches, doctors and problems.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can also serve as a good starting point for the next generation of science fiction writers, Cory Doctorow's famous novel "Scroogled" describes with Orwellian reminiscences a future in which you can get a good approximation of a person using only data from Google.
The double murderer from Ozd was helped by two teenagers to clear his tracks
Two teenagers were questioned by police in the case of double murder in Ozd, and according to reasonable suspicions, they helped to remove the traces of this crime, said a spokesman for the Supreme Police Directorate of the County of Borsod on Tuesday.
The individuals involved in the activities they were suspected of have confessed and are currently charged with aiding and abetting a criminal offence.
Both juveniles, according to MTI, two girls, are wanted in the wild.
Aiding and abetting is punishable by up to five years in prison.
The suspect in the double murder in Oświęcim, a 23-year-old local man, was taken into custody on Sunday.
He's a suspect in a crime of premeditated multiple homicide for motive.
During the investigation, it was revealed that a 23-year-old young man owed a 53-year-old man a larger sum.
The suspect did not want to pay his debt, so he lured his creditor to a shop in Ozd last Wednesday, where he killed first a man and then his 9-year-old daughter.
According to the information of the MTI, the young man was preparing to commit the crime in advance, as evidenced by the fact that he committed the murder with a weapon hidden at the crime scene.
