A smart car simulates the flight of a bumblebee
What better way to develop collision-avoidance technologies than by imitating the obstacle detectors found in the natural world?
Like the bees.
The original strategic idea for this startling project, unveiled at Japan's CEATEC, was given to Nissan engineers by the bees, to build a new generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed a biomimetic robotic driving system, the BR23C, a robotic mini-car that is equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective envelope", explained Kazuhiro Doi, the brand's general manager for technology PR and R&D, at the exhibition.
The important role of the compound eyes is that they allow bees to see in all directions at more than 300 degrees of vision.
To replicate the function of the compound eye, engineers used the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 m in front of the BR23C in a 180° field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor which is immediately converted into a collision avoidance operation.
The obstacle is captured for a fraction of a second, after which the robotic car begins to imitate the bee's movements and, by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid a collision, immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If it were not, the robot car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Lab and the robot car project.
They must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology fits into the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shield, within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to mirror what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
This process can't take more than the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, this movement cannot be up, down, or angular, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction that the wheels can turn.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to the bees in avoiding, only the rotational, acceleration and deceleration of the robot car was applied.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life span than lithium-ion variants.
Ando says instinctive, intelligent reactions are important, not the ability to process, much less store, data.
This mechanism must process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
It doesn't need to store and react to them using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a memory of a few kilobytes at a time.
It doesn't need gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in developing an immediate avoidance technology that Nissan estimates could be in production within a decade.
Another application may be to connect the unit to a GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles in the road, would take the motorist to the final destination specified.
