The bill for a $700 billion rescue package, to be split into several installments, aimed at buying back the banks' subprime loans, is already in writing.
Half the amount will be used in the first round.
After further negotiations that ended after midnight U.S. Eastern time on Saturday, congressional representatives reached agreement in days of debate on a $700 billion bailout package, Reuters reported.
"We have made significant progress", announced Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic speaker of the House of Representatives, who said the only thing left to do was to write a deal.
The compromise on the package was also supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said of the compromise result: "The program will work and be effective, but further action is needed".
The paper version of the package was released before the Asian markets opened on Sunday at 8pm Washington time (i.e. Monday at 2am Central European time), but did not cause any significant upswing on the stock exchanges.
The bill, the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, which is to establish the program will be voted on Monday first by the House of Representatives, then by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi Saturday night, after which news of the deal was welcomed at the White House as well.
"We are pleased with the progress made last night and greatly appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy", said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
The program is different from the original proposal of the Bush administration, which was to spend $700 billion in one go to buy back bad mortgage-backed securities.
Now, it is possible to spend up to half of the $700 billion in the first round, with $250 billion to be spent immediately after Congress is expected to decide on the matter on Monday, with the Treasury Department buying mortgage-backed securities that are rated as subprime, and the fate of the remaining $100 billion then resting on the president's decision.
The program will be overseen by a special committee, which will include the chairman of the Federal Reserve.
The second half of the $700 billion budget is contingent on further Congressional action.
The Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic within the meaning of the law: it can simultaneously buy back sub-standard loans, mortgages and securities backed by mortgages, or other "poisonous" loans.
The purchase can be done through auctions or directly, the competent officials of the ministry said.
The legal provision will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance scheme whereby the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee for the funds constituting a cause for concern, in return for which the company will pay a price corresponding to the expected losses.
As Henry Paulson said, the act provides the necessary resources to spend up to $700 billion to meet the urgent requirements of the U.S. financial system, whether it's buying large amounts of bad assets, insuring them, or preventing systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the big money institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed", he added.
The bankers who are in trouble and waiting for government help can count on the government to cut their severance pay - which in overseas slang is simply called "the golden parachute".
Their payment will be limited in certain cases only, and these limits will depend on the type of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction basically means that if the department buys through the auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on the gold pads unless the failed bank directors are sent straight to retirement.
In the case of direct repurchase of subprime loans, the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that the money for management is not overspent.
It should be added that the existing contracts for gold parachutes will not be changed, the restriction only concerns new contracts, which is intended to be an additional incentive to participate in the programme.
"This is the first time in American history that a statutory limitation on CEO compensation will be in effect", said the chairman of the House Financial Services Committee, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the State will have a right to acquire a stake in the banks participating in the scheme, thereby reducing the risk for taxpayers, since once the economy and, with it, the rescued bank, is back on its feet, they can profit from the transaction.
The plan calls for the president to submit a bill to Congress within the next five years, setting out how taxpayers can recover the expected losses from the financial sector.
Of course, there were also voices of doubt on both sides of the issue.
"This is not what the American people asked for, because this is not what taxpayer dollars will protect", said Rep. Darrell Issa, Republican from California.
His Democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, said the passage of the provision was pushed by the very people responsible for the Wall Street crash.
Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0,1% in August 2008 compared to the previous month and by 12,9% compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office reported.
Industry export sales prices were 1,1% higher than in July 2008 and decreased by 3,9% year on year.
Industrial production prices, which accounted for the changes in domestic and export prices, were 0,7% higher than in the previous month, and increased by 3,2% year on year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased only slightly, by 0.1 percent, compared with the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in manufacturing industries also increased slightly by 0.1% compared to July.
The largest price increases were in the leather and footwear sector in August 2008 (2,8%) mainly due to the monthly price increases of 4,6% in the manufacture of leather and footwear and 2,5% in the manufacture of footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical materials and products manufacturing sector (1.6%).
Prices fell in the oil processing industry (1.4%), in the electrical machinery industry (0.9%) and, to a minimum, in the woodworking industry (0.1%).
Prices in the papermaking and publishing and printing industries remained unchanged.
In other manufacturing sectors, we have measured price increases in the range of 0.2 to 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water generation and distribution sector, which has a large weight in domestic industrial sales, prices rose by 0,3% in August, mainly as a continuing effect of the officially established gas price increase from 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison of domestic sales by manufacturing industry, prices increased most in the petroleum processing industry (32.4 per cent).
The metalworking industry saw a price increase of 13.2% and the food, beverage and tobacco industry, which is the most important, saw a price increase of 11%.
The price decrease was recorded in the textile and textile products industry (2.5%) and in the electrical machinery and equipment industry (0.3%).
In the other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price growth ranged between 0.6% and 9.1%.
Overall, manufacturing prices rose by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sectors exceeded those of the previous year by 18,7%.
In terms of a breakdown by sector, the highest monthly price increase (0.7%) in August was seen in the sectors involved in the production of tangible assets.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3%, while in the energy and manufacturing sectors, prices were unchanged from the previous month.
The largest price increase compared with the same month of the previous year was observed in August 2008 in the energy-producing and further-processing sectors (16.8%).
In the consumer goods sectors, we recorded a 6.8% increase in prices, while in the tangible assets sectors, a 1.4% decrease.
The export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1% in August compared with the previous month, and decreased by 3.9% in the 12-month comparison.
Our domestic currency depreciated against the euro by 1.7 percent, against the dollar by 7.1 percent, against the euro by 7.5 percent and against the dollar by 15.9 percent in one month compared to August 2007.
