MP3 players, the charges, put your hearing at risk.
Listening to loud music for long periods and using portable music players like MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
According to a communication published today by the European Commission, which in an official report circulated in Brussels quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Health Risks that have recently emerged and been identified (Csrseri) by the European Commission, the European Commission has published a report on the health risks of the European Union's food supply.
"From this scientific opinion, we read in footnotes, it follows that 5-10% of those who listen to music for at least five years with portable music devices, for more than an hour a day a week, and who keep the device on a high volume, are at risk of permanent hearing loss".
"I am concerned that so many young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at high acoustic levels may unknowingly damage their hearing in an irreparable way", admits Meglena Kuneva.
'Scientific evidence  continues  shows a clear risk and a need to react quickly.
The most important thing is that we need to stimulate consumers and get this information out there.
We must continue to re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific finding, so that they become fully effective and keep pace with new technology.'
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine this problem in view of the high use of portable musical instruments and the increasing number of young people exposed to noise of this origin.
'The scientists  concluded the Eu  Executive Officer confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine, together with the other members and parties who raised the issue, what measures could possibly be put in place to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise caused by portable musical instruments and similar devices.'
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that may be caused by excessive exposure to similar forms of noise.
It is very possible to limit these damages by finding solutions such as reducing the level and duration of exposure.
The Scientific Committee of the European Communities believes that users of portable musical instruments, if they use loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only five hours a week, exceed the current limits corresponding to the maximum noise level allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for long periods of time risk permanent hearing loss after five years.
This problem is thought to affect 5-10% of users of such devices and may affect between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
