The Elite in Danger
This was demonstrated a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion bailout proposed by the White House: a large number of Americans were more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
As yesterday's New York Times reported, the current crisis is dividing the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, more moderate, sympathetic to the federal institutions and business community, and its new soul, conservative, hostile to Washington and the financial world, strong in the Midwest and South.
The soul who arrogantly expressed the vote I spoke of at the beginning...
But this is just one example of the changes, the big changes that the current economic earthquake is already showing: not only in the United States, but in the whole West and maybe not just here.
In the United States and Europe, this crisis seems to be acting as an accelerator of long-in-cubation phenomena that are consolidating in a new climate and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is reactualization, an extraordinary market revival, a dual category of State power in relation to a certain re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions, which of course have strong ties abroad, but in which the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state, are most heavily involved.
And that also created a political problem for those who run it: that is, how to respond to the grievances and protests of people and families who are, among other things, voters.
In short, the crisis appears to be economically global, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be largely out of the picture or to have little to add: the clearest proof of this is the European Union, which is divided as always between different interests and different national strategies and which is unable to decide on a common political line.
And so they're all waiting for the government of each individual country to step in, to rescue, to revive the market, to set new rules and, most importantly, to allocate funds: at the moment when we get into a pinch, only the states have the economic means, the amount of financial resources, to be able to try and put things right.
And they also have the necessary means and the authority to use them: two resources of immense value, under certain circumstances, that no market and no international organization could ever have in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the national state is in line with the growing importance of recent economic developments, which tend to attribute to a factor closely related to it: territorial affiliation.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we believed that we had entered the realm of the more and more sophisticated, immaterial technology, while we believed that global finance was destined to rule the world, we suddenly realized that our future would have to be increasingly confronted with such immaterial things as water, grain, oil.
All things, anyone would say, can be transported from one place on earth to another, but they are, in any case, absolutely bound to a limited space, a territory.
So whoever becomes their ruler has a lot more cards on his sleeve than whoever doesn't and whoever has the misfortune of living in a place with no grain, no oil, and no water.
I'm getting to the second novelty, but it's a bad omen.
When you talk about territory, state, government, you're inevitably talking about politics, which is leadership.
In view of the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena appear to be emerging.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritarian leadership, a demand for someone who can take the lead.
On the other hand, a wave of discrediting of the existing leadership, especially the economic one, which proved equally unconventional and full of dark places.
And together with that something even deeper and in some ways disturbing: the discredit, the impatience, the sense of incompetence and the absence that the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries is trying to control.
It seems that the belief is spreading more and more among the masses of the population that their actions are the same as the ideas of the still popular elite, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the true sense of the word, that the elite has already outlived its time and is indifferent to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership is simply a subterranean one-branch movement, but the powerful movement to remove the ruling classes and the traditional political order is manifested in sudden electoral "wings" or unexpected shifts in collective mood in the last and most recent period, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavoria to the fall of the Labour Party in Britain, to the revolt of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their ceremonies, their newspapers, their accredited intelligentsia, someone would say their format, have increasingly more problems to understand, that is to represent, what, not from today, is being created in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is again strengthening, growing, potentially too strong.
Before that, it would be an exaggeration to talk about a permanent "mass uprising".
But we certainly can't say that it means keeping our eyes wide open.
