Open Office, we have the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package.
It's the day of Open Office.org 3.0, an open source, custom-made package that's going to reach a growing number of users, from the home to the office, from professionals to the public administration, as a free alternative to the more familiar Microsoft Office.
After about a year of work by volunteers, controlled by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now available to the general public with various innovations: to the welcome screen and the revised and improved opening window, there are added other, far more significant, such as compatibility for the operating system Apple Mac OS X and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2, the latest standard version of ISO.
Emphasis is also placed on collaboration with Office 2007, Open Office is able to open the document even with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Of interest are the special features of some models, such as the ability to reduce the size of a PowerPoint presentation, useful for e.g. electronic transmission, or the ability to transfer a PDF file to a graphic design model and retain the original appearance of the page.
From this perspective, we can create "PDF hybrids" that resemble typical Adobe graphics and have the properties of a spreadsheet or word processor.
Collaboration is an element that has received many improvements within application programs: in Excel it is possible to work together between different users and avoid conflicts on changes, in the text program each collaborator is assigned one color to the comments to be more clear identification in the revision phase.
Some companies are also working on bringing some of the Open Office features to the web (on the cloud), and should have a final result in the coming weeks.
The Italian version can be downloaded from http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html, it was added to the English version, which is on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the package is also available for the Linux operating system.
The installation CD can also be sent to your home or workplace on request.
And if the theme of free of charge can be a trigger for expansion in households, it is precisely in the commercial area that the Open Office package is betting a lot, and it can already count on a variety of projects implemented in public administration and schools.
And there is no shortage of training, consultancy and support services ideal for SMEs, which could open up business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main models: Writer, for video writing, replacing Word; Calc, a spreadsheet processor that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for PowerPoint-like presentations; Dbase, as in the case of the more famous Access, a program that allows you to work on databases; and Draw, finally, a graphics model.
The target for 2008 is 5 million downloads, and considering that we're almost at 3.6 million downloads today, with the new release it's possible that this number could be surpassed.
