Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso, the city is demolishing the historic halls
The historic movie theaters are closing in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without a cinema is like a blind man, like a face without eyes".
The film, presented by director Giuseppe Tornator, successfully documents what is happening in the big Italian urban centres as well as in the rural towns.
The process of the reduction of cinemas, the birth of large multi-screen cinema in the suburbs and the subsequent demise of single-screen cinema in the city centre, is one of those events that seems inevitable and irreversible, but also has all the hallmarks of a true cultural crime.
Often, historical places filled with memories disappear, "it's like losing a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a journey and a lot of emotions", says the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film which won the Tornator Oscar and the Grand Jury Prize at Cannes 20 years ago, and which told the story of a village cinema and the sadness of a way of life that cinema had lost forever.
The figures obtained by the ANECE, the main association of operators, speak for themselves: in the last five years 316 traditional type cinemas have closed their doors, with the highest billing going to the most important cinemas: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures, Emilia-Romagna is in first place with 82 cinema halls lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And as proof that the rise of multiplexes is the first to cause them to disappear, these three Italian regions have recorded the highest number of new multiplex cinemas: 195 more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 more in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
'The Italian approach has developed irrationally', says Paolo Protti, President of Anecu, 'it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that the existing ones will survive, because when one cinema in a city closes, not all its visitors are willing to move to a multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund for the operators: the previous state debt is around 10 million euros.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it's a disgrace that the government doesn't respect existing laws.
Between 16 and 18 million euro per year would be needed to support the sector.
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city to have a problem with closures and to have decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas both in the historic centre and in the suburbs.
Among the planned standards are tax relief measures for operators and mobility benefits for the public: spectators will be able to drive to the restricted traffic zone and will have special prices for stopping and in some car parks.
'I like this initiative' says Giuseppe Tornatore, 'and I hope other cities will follow Bologna's example by introducing other measures.
