Giorgio Dal Torrione, chairman of the Christian Democrats, who, at the moment of dissolution, was elected head of the centre-right coalition after a close election in May.
He cried out over the scandal when the Prefecture ordered the dissolution of the city council.
He called the then Deputy Minister of the Interior, Marco Minniti, to account, accusing him of plotting for political reasons, but the judges in the arrest warrant signed this morning explain that the Mafia group even went so far as to request a change in the A3 highway project.
Further questioning ordered against Dal Torrione, writes the public prosecutor, revealed "a willingness to shift the claims of a businessman, a representative of some larger group very close, as is commonly known, to Piromallim and to adapt the elections of the public administration to the interests of the mafia group".
When energy is born from waves, the big ones come into play.
It's an infinite pool that covers over 70% of the Earth's surface and is now being explored by the world's major energy companies.
The waves, the currents, the tides, the ebbs are new sources of inexhaustible energy, caught in the eye of giants like Chevron, who are now trying to get their hands on these sources.
The possibility of generating energy from the sea's movements has been studied for more than a century, and research intensified in the 1970s in the wake of the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil fell in the 1980's, the idea of using marine energy was dropped, but now environmental organizations and new oil price increases have given the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London in 2007 said that about 15 percent of the world's electricity consumption could be covered by the use of the movement of the waves of the sea.
That would be twice the amount of energy that is currently produced in nuclear power plants.
Plus, there are tides and currents.
The giants are attacking.
The company that invested in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 agreed to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the plan was announced, it seemed like a huge, revolutionary move.
After two years of betting on marine energy, more and more companies are betting on marine energy rather than traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technology", a spokesman for a company linked to the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering a partnership with us".
The cooperation we're considering involves getting the U.S. Energy Commission's permits necessary to launch a project to harness marine energy in Alaska.
We cannot ignore this signal, especially when we consider that Alaska is where the US continues to drill for oil, and where President Bush recently announced plans for new drilling.
Besides Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are tracking the trail of marine energy, and the sums invested so far, although not detailed, are seen by observers as showing growing interest.
Technology that needs to be developed.
Experts speak of a technology that is still in its infancy, because the environmental impact of harnessing marine energy is unknown.
For now, the installations in Portugal and some in Scotland are small and do not appear to be causing any major problems to the ecosystem.
But to produce more energy, we need to use technologies with a greater impact on the environment.
The methods are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys that are interconnected.
The force of the waves that move the buoys up and down is converted by means of cylinders and cylinders into hydraulic pressure inside the buoys.
Pressure spins the turbine, which supplies power to the generator.
Power is being fed to the shore by undersea cables.
There are currently four such facilities in the design phase, which are only awaiting federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for military purposes.
In contrast, Verdant Power already generates power for the shopping mall and parking lot using six offshore turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water during the ebb and flow of the tide causes turbines to turn, and this turbulent motion powers the generator.
Verdant said they have a long list of clients waiting for the necessary permits to use the energy.
By the waves, by the tide, by the tide.
Of particular interest at this time is the potential of tidal currents, say at the Electric Power Research Institute.
Although it is a non-contiguous factor, the tides are more predictable than the wind, the sun or the waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is in tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with other coastal states, have already invested $7.5 million in 2008 and are forecasting investments of up to $35 million for 2009.
